==== reject the traditional account of knowledge and reasoning ====
The third alternative is to reject the traditional account of knowledge and
reasoning. Reject the claim that our capacity to reason involves the ability to
distinguish necessary from contingent truths and abandon Aristotle's claim that
the best form of knowledge involves being aware <q>that it is not possible for
[the thing known] to be otherwise</q>(([[local:zz.texts/aristotle-completeWorks.oxfordRevisedTrans.pdf|_Posterior Analytics_, Book I, §2]])). In particular, reject the distinction
between necessary and contingent truths, and offer in its place an alternative
account of what it is about supposedly necessary truths that allows us to (more
or less reliably) distinguish them.

